## Recall Stats: A Sobering Reality

We are only halfway through April, yet the total number of recalls this year has reached 302, already nearing half of the all-time recalls. Among these, 84 are Class I recalls, signifying a serious health risk.

## Salmonella Strikes Dairy Products Again

Lone Star Dairy Products LLC issued a Class I recall for their Spray Dried Dairy Powder due to Salmonella contamination detected during routine testing. With Salmonella accounting for 104 recalls so far this year, it remains one of the most persistent threats in the industry.

## Foreign Objects and Labeling Issues Persist

JFE Franchising Inc had a series of recalls for their dumplings, all due to glass fragments found in the products. Mislabeling also caused recalls, such as The Maros Group's undeclared milk in their Prickly Pear Jelly and undeclared sulfites in Mama Rose's Prickly Pear Salad Dressing. These cases highlight ongoing challenges with packaging and labeling compliance.

## Novel Issues in Drinks

Pocas International Corp. faced multiple Class III recalls for their Popping Boba RTD teas due to packaging integrity issues. Meanwhile, HEYTEA USA INC recalled their Coconut Drink due to undeclared milk, raising concerns over allergen management in imported products.

## Repeat Offenders

Certain brands continue to appear on recall lists. Moonlight Packing Corporation and Albertsons Companies LLC are among those with dismal recall grades and histories of issues. This trend emphasizes the need for stricter quality controls and accountability.

## A Call for Vigilance

With approximately 59 recalls in April alone, the food industry's systemic issues are evident. Consumers and regulators must remain vigilant. The only way forward is ensuring transparency and compliance across the supply chain.
